segments.text: Now you seem to be describing a campus which was comparatively free of bias and prejudice.
Is that correct?
Well, I would say that there was no overt conduct of that nature.
Because, I mean, I think being an Aggie was very important to everybody.
It's more or less when you group people together, and I had always felt a part of the Aggie family.
I think there had been, most of the wrath that came at that time, again, given the historical perspective, was a lot from the core versus the non-rag.
And so...
We had heard that there were students who were being quadded on San Jacinto Day, which was a day, as you know, where Sam Houston defeated Santa Ana.
And it was done along the same kind of line of the quadding they did when
if it was your birthday or if it was some other day.
So some of us kind of felt uncomfortable about that.
I don't think that we, you saw a, I never saw the Confederate flag flown, not that that represents any kind of bigotry or any kind of negative feeling.
But you never saw people using, at least I never heard, derogatory terms about African Americans or Hispanics.
It was just an air of disconnectedness, and I think that was what was happening.

I don't think that the administration fully, fully understood that as these cultures were coming together, especially during the 60s, late 60s, and there was a whole segment of the community across the state that was saying, Hispanics, you are, assert your rights, assert your rights.
Well, that's going to impact students.
I don't think that there was a sense in the administration to say,
We need to be doing something to transition or to make sure that there's some connectivity.
I think as we began to raise these concerns, the university responded by saying, OK, well, if you're committed to an organization of this sort, we'll work with you.
And of course, they funded that.
And it's still in existence.
It's been in existence over 25 years.
Did you ever experience either an intentional or unintentional verbal misstatement, ethnic statement, by a faculty member, say, in a class or a lecture?
Do you remember anything anybody said?
No.
No, I didn't.
It's interesting because I did later as a graduate student, but not as an undergrad.
But as an undergrad, never.

Because I think there was a, and I think this professor who used the word wetback in one of his classes, he was not using it, he was using it in a, it was a wage and salary class, and he was, we were describing contract labor, we were describing how you determine wages and salaries, and he said,
Well, this assumed a case study in XYZ, and he says, now, none of these are wetbacks, meaning, in his mind, they're not just being hired off the street or without any kind of rules.
He was trying to say it in a clinical context, but I later on found out he was not a Texan, and I think he had picked up the word as a word to use to describe.
And didn't even know what he was saying.
You know, it was kind of, but it was not in a, he did not use it in a derogatory sense, more as a descriptive, because that's what, in fact, I had the same thing happen in law school.
one of my professors describing the situation, he used the word wetback.
Well, this is in Washington, D.C. And he had no clue that that had negative connotations in certain parts of Texas.
I'm grinning because a couple, three weeks ago, I filled in for John Hoyle in one of Tony Brown's classes for the doctors of veterinary medicine, meat inspectors.
Oh, yeah.
And by the time we get to this

incident I'm going to mention everybody was fairly well acquainted and here's a big good natured black man and I was trying to get them to think of terms that they should not use or if they did to be very very careful in how they used them
And I was saying that the word for people of African ancestry that is easiest to use without any problem is to say the word black.
I said, you can't mispronounce it.
Black and white is parallel.
Because I said, if you use the word negro, that can get mispronounced a bit and so forth.
Well, about this time, this good-natured black man raises his hand.
Big, well-fed.
And he's saying, well, that reminds me of one.
I can't understand why rednecks get unhappy if one of us uses that term.
Because after all, they call each other rednecks.
Why can't the rest of us?
Well, the whole room exploded in laughter at him and started... And he was going, oh!
And it was as if, my goodness, I never thought of that.
And they were teasing him about, you know...
And I told him, I said, well, the equivalent on this campus would be those of us that have a long tie to Texas A&M, we enjoy telling Aggie jokes.
But we sure don't want somebody wearing an orange T-shirt to tell an Aggie joke, particularly if it's in front of a large crowd of other than Aggies.
And he began to say, oh, okay, shake his head.
All right, in that same era, we're at war in Vietnam.
What do you remember during those days about the protests and so forth on the campus, if any?
The only thing I remember was there was a move towards a war moratorium.
And students wore black bands around their arms.
And that was the most that one ever saw.
Quite frankly, you could
you could be at A&M and not realize that there was a war.
I mean, one could say that in a negative and positive way.
I don't think there was a question that...
I mean, the sense of loyalty was, I guess, what...
permeated the whole thing that, you know, we're the United States, we're at war, let's support it.
It was that mindset.

And so those who were seeking to wear their armbands, and I remember seeing some students, you know, you didn't see people harassing them or chastising them, you know, but they were a few that would wear their armbands.
And of course, that in itself was somewhat of a radical act on campus.
Do you remember anything ever happening in a class that had anything to do with the protest?
No.
I think that would be like
It would never happen.
You would never think it would happen anyway.
You began as a freshman in Mr. Rutter's last year.
Did you as a student have any impression of him?
If so, what was your impression?
Well, I think all of us who had grown up around this area particularly had a lot of admiration for him.
He was considered a very... His name, Olin Teague, all those were very
honored men at the time and I remember meeting General Rudder once.
I can't remember what the occasion was.
It was some function and shook hands and of course I felt quite honored and quite much, you know, felt like, wow, this is a real moment.
And so, I mean, I think there was a, it was that sense.
I mean, it was, I guess back in the 60s was the days where you could tell these
stories of heroes and still feel good about it and not be cynical about, you know, that we have heroes, and he was one of those.
All right, then he died, and after General Ludeke was the interim, Jack Williams became president.
Did you have any interaction with him?
Yes, not as a student, but later as assistant director of admissions.
What was your impression of him?
Oh, I thought he was brilliant.
He was quite an eloquent man.
He had a tremendous voice.
I mean, his
I don't know if you want to call it baritone or something.
He had a great way of communicating.
I remember one commencement exercise, because I had to help be a marshal at all these commencement exercises.
I remember a speech on Murphy's Law.
And I don't know if you remember, but I remember hearing that.
And of course, he was hilarious.
I mean, in his dry wit and his dry humor, he talked about Murphy's Law and all the different laws that would follow.
I also had occasion to, I applied for a job when I was, I had been working here and I applied for a job with the chancellor's office.
And I was not the strongest candidate, but I was a strong candidate.
And another person got selected.
And so I wrote him a letter saying, Dr. Williams, I just want to tell you that I am very interested in working with the university.
And it was a positive letter.
I wanted to give it a positive spin.
And I said, I wanted just to let you know that I appreciate you considering my application.
and look forward to working in the future with the administration, something like that.
And I just let it go.
But then about a week later, he wrote me a letter.
It's his personal letter.
It's, Danielle, I want to thank you for your leadership.
I mean, it made me feel good.
He says, and let me assure you, your future is very bright here at Texas A&M.
Signed, Jack K. Wilkes.
It made me feel great.
I mean, so, and of course, as things happened a year later, a year and a half later, vacancy came up.
I applied and got selected.
So, you know, those things you can't forget because those are very important.
And so it's those little moments that you, and of course, one time when I met him at the Citizens Building,

it was almost as if you were going to see God, because in a huge systems administration building, and of course I never had been in a huge, magnificent building like that before, and you saw him sitting there, and it was a great feeling to know him.
And of course, you'd see him later, he was with the congressman, or he was with this or that, so you felt good about having talked to him.
I was like,
in my early twenties.
Did you think he had a sense of humor?
Yeah, he did.
I think he did.
I think he had a good sense of humor.
Again, I liked his dry wit.
What struck me was he's not comical, but he was very humorous.
I mean, he could say things, and it had so much humor in it, but he kept his dignity about him, which is something that I guess some people lose when they're trying to be comical or being humorous.
At Clemson, his nickname was Smiling Jack.
That's what the students called him because they thought that he was always upbeat and positive.
Let's see.
No particular relations with any of the deans while you were a student.
No.
Nor board members or anything like that.
Was...
Did you and your buddies talk about Vietnam and what effect that might have on you?
Well, yeah.
My lottery number was 239.
And the year that the lottery went in when I was, it went as high as 199.
And I remember sitting and listening on the radio and they were announcing these over the radio.
And I guess I just sort of like had a,
feeling the relief, like, wow, my number's not going to be reached.
Because they had said a certain number as far as they're going to go.
I didn't, you know, it's strange, but I don't remember very, very many who went to Vietnam from here.
Now, of course, they may have and never came back.
But, you know, Brine County Station was a pretty sleepy, quiet town at that time.
And what time do you need to leave?
In about another minute.
Oh, okay.
Well, let's stop right here.
Okay.
Let's stop here.
Okay.
Yeah, I've got a couple of things I need to do.
